{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1c85edd8-897d-42c5-9cb1-2a71d995dd92","content":"A **NullReferenceException** is an application-level runtime error — it means your code is dereferencing a `null` reference. This is **not** a CLR activation issue.\n\n**CLR activation logs** diagnose problems like:\n- Wrong .NET runtime version being loaded\n- Runtime failing to load at all\n- Unexpected Framework-on-Demand dialogs\n\nThey won't help with a `NullReferenceException`.\n\n**To debug your crash, you'll want to:**\n1. Check the **stack trace** from the exception — it tells you the exact line/method where `null` was accessed.\n2. Look at **Event Viewer** (Application log) or your app's log output.\n3. Use a debugger (`dotnet run` with breakpoints, or attach Visual Studio).\n\nDo you have a stack trace, crash dump, or log output you can share? I can help you analyze that instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4db65837-66e9-4b54-bc20-8a821c75ae11","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. They mention CLR activation logs specifically. Let me check if the relevant skill is available.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which is described as: \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, a NullReferenceException after startup is not really a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs are about how the CLR runtime is loaded/selected by the shim (mscoree.dll) — things like which runtime version gets picked, whether the right framework is found, etc. \n\nA NullReferenceException is a runtime application-level bug, not a CLR activation problem. I should be straightforward with the user about this mismatch rather than trying to force a skill that won't actually help diagnose their issue.","outputTokens":433,"requestId":"2C44:97105:138BBC7:1643